What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset originally contains information about 183,412 gobike rides in the San Francisco Bay area with 16 attributes, detailing the times of rental and return, names of rental station and return, and information about the people borrowing the bikes.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in how the customer and subscriber user-types differ from one another.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the distance covered, the time of the day, age and gender attributes are important features to help understand the differences and patterns between the two user groups.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I'd be looking to investigate the distribution of individual variables and to achieve this I'd be answering the following questions:

  • What is the distribution of the different users?
  • What is the gender distribution of riders?
  • What is the age distribution of riders?
  • What time of the day are most rides taken?
  • What day of the week are most rides taken?
  • What is the distribution of ride duration?
  • What is the distribution of distance covered?

Question¶

What is the distribution of the different users?

Visualization¶

In [11]:
#funtion to label x and y axis and plot titles
def label(x, y, title):
    """
    x(str): x-axis title
    y(str): y-axis title
    title: Plot main title
    
    Returns: None
    """
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y)
    plt.title(title, pad=20);

In [38]:
#Defining a function to convert latitude & longitude coords to kms using geopy library so .apply method can be used on all rows.
import geopy.distance
def distance(coords1, coords2):
    return round(geopy.distance.geodesic(coords1, coords2).km, 2)

gobike['distance'] = gobike.apply(lambda x: distance((x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude']), 
                                                       (x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude'])), axis=1)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The age distribution was heavily skewed to the right so I looked at the data using a log transform. It can be seen on the log transform that the age distribution is unimodal.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When investigating the distribution of ride duration it was observed that the outliers had 0km covered in distance suggesting that they never left the station. Since more information wasn't available to examine that, the outliers were removed from the dataset.

Observation¶

Since there is a positive correlation between distance and duration of trips, it can be implied that there would be no correlation between ages and duration of trips.

It was observed that Customers spend more time and go longer distances on their rides than an average Subscriber would. Also, the most trips are taken on Thursdays, more than any other day. The least trips are taken on weekends.

As expected, there is a positive correlation between distance of trips and their duration but the age of users have no influence on the distance and duration.
